    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "7-13",
      "detail": "5th in AL East",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays have stopped swinging. After four consecutive defeats - including <strong>last night's 6-2 loss to Arizona, where Corbin Carroll's grand slam in the eighth inning broke the game open</strong> - Toronto has collapsed from contention into the AL East basement. At 7-13, five games behind the division lead and languishing in fifth place, this isn't a slump anymore. It's a crisis of execution. The Jays managed just two runs on twelve hits against the Diamondbacks, stranding eight runners in scoring position. That's not bad luck. That's baseball abandoning them at the plate when it matters most. Jeff Hoffman, who saved 33 games last season, couldn't navigate the eighth. The bullpen folded. The bats went silent. Everything that should work for a contender has inverted into a death spiral. <strong>They face Arizona again today at 3:10 PM ET in the series finale</strong> - a chance to salvage something from this wreckage before the calendar turns to May and this season becomes something far darker than early-season turbulence.",
        "updated": "Updated April 19, 2026"
      },
